"Rabatel A., Deline P., Jaillet S., Ravanel L.","Rock falls in high-alpine rock walls quantified by terrestrial lidar measurements: A case study in the Mont Blanc area",2008,"Geophysical Research Letters","35","10", L10502,"","",,,10.1029/2008GL033424,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-58049121924&partnerID=40&md5=78239695b72a27c17e92eade631fc28a","Laboratoire Edytem, CNRS, Université de Savoie, F-73376 Le Bourget du Lac, France","Rabatel, A., Laboratoire Edytem, CNRS, Université de Savoie, F-73376 Le Bourget du Lac, France; Deline, P., Laboratoire Edytem, CNRS, Université de Savoie, F-73376 Le Bourget du Lac, France; Jaillet, S., Laboratoire Edytem, CNRS, Université de Savoie, F-73376 Le Bourget du Lac, France; Ravanel, L., Laboratoire Edytem, CNRS, Université de Savoie, F-73376 Le Bourget du Lac, France","The global warming observed in recent decades and its future increase may affect permafrost distribution on high-mountain faces with consequences for their stability. In this paper, we show that rock falls from high-alpine rock walls can be computed with a decimetre-resolution using lidar measurements. A laser scanner was used to create point clouds and triangulated irregular network models on the east face of the Tour Ronde at 3792 m asl (Mont Blanc massif). Comparison of the models realised from measurements of July 2005 and July 2006 enabled quantification of rock falls with reduced uncertainty. The volume of rock fall reached a total of 536 m3 in the scanned area, which matches an erosion rate of 8.4 mm yr-1. This rate slightly higher to the ones reported in former studies enable to assume that this rock fall may be the sequence of the permafrost degradation in this rock face. Copyright 2008 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Erosion; Global warming; Military operations; Optical radar; Permafrost; Soil mechanics; Uncertainty analysis; Case studies; Erosion rates; Laser scanners; Lidar measurements; Permafrost degradations; Permafrost distributions; Point clouds; Rock falls; Rock walls; Terrestrial lidars; Triangulated irregular network models; Rocks; alpine environment; debris flow; erosion rate; lidar; permafrost; rockfall; triangulated irregular network; uncertainty analysis; Alps; Eurasia; Europe; France; Haute Savoie; Mont Blanc; Rhone-Alpes; Savoy Alps; Western Alps; Western Europe",,,,,,"Barla, G., Dutto, F., Mortara, G., Brenva glacier rock avalanche of 18 January 1997 on the Mont Blanc range, northwest Italy, (2000) Landslide News, pp. 13-15,2; Deline, P., Permafrost and rock falls in high mountain: The Drus (Mont Blanc massif, France) (2006) Geophys. Res. Abstr, 8, p. 02033; Deline, P., and the PERMAdataROC team (2007), The relation of permafrost degradation and slope instabilities in high-Alpine steep rockwalls (Mont Blanc massif and Matterhorn): The research project PERMAdataROC, Geophys. Res. Abstr., 9, 07191Francou, B., (1993) Hautes Montagnes, Passion dExploration, , 202 pp, Masson, Paris; Gruber, S., Haeberli, W., Permafrost in steep bedrock slopes and its temperature-related destabilization following climate change (2007), F02S18, doi:10.1029/2006JF000547Gruber, S., Hoelzle, M., Statistical modelling of mountain permafrost distribution: Local calibration and incorporation of remotely sensed data (2001) Permaftost Periglacial Processes, 12 (1), pp. 69-77; Gruber, S., Surface temperatures in steep alpine rock faces-A strategy for regional-scale measurement and modeling (2003) Proceedings of the Eighth International Conference on Permaftost, pp. 325-330. , edited by M. Phillips, S. M. Springman, and L. U. Arenson, pp, A. A. Balkema, Brookfield, Vt; Gruber, S., M. Hoelzle, and W. Haeberli (2004), Permafrost thaw and destabilization of Alpine rock walls in the hot summer of 2003, Geophys. Res. Lett., 31, L13504, doi:10.1029/2004GL020051Haeberli, W., Beniston, M., Climate change and its impacts on glaciers and permafrost in the Alps (1998) Ambio, 27 (4), pp. 258-265; Haeberli, W., The Kolka-Karmadon rock/ice slide of 20 September 2002: An extraordinary event of historical dimensions in North Ossetia, Russian Caucasus (2004) J. Glaciol, 50 (171), pp. 533-546; Haeberli, W., Permafrost creep and rock glacier dynamics (2006) Permafrost Periglacial Processes, 17, pp. 189-214; Humlum, O., The geomorphic significance of rock glaciers: Estimates of rock glacier debris volumes and headwall recession rates in W Greenland (2000) Geomorphology, 35, pp. 41-67; James, T.D., Extracting photogrammetric ground control from lidar DEMs for change detection (2006) Photogramm. Rec, 21 (116), pp. 312-328; Lemke, P., et al. (2007), Observations: Changes in snow, ice and frozen ground, in Climate Change 2007: The Physical Science Basis, edited by S. Solomon et al., pp. 337-383, Cambridge Univ. Press, New YorkNoetzli, J., S. Gruber, T. Kohl, N. Salzmann, and W. Haeberli (2007), Three-dimensional distribution and evolution of permafrost temperatures in idealized high-mountain topography, J. Geophys. Res., 112, F02S13, doi:10.1029/2006JF000545Pirulli, M., The Thurwieser rock avalanche, Italian Alps: Description and dynamic analysis (2006) Geophys. Res. Abstr, 8, p. 08482; Rabatel, A., The use of laserscanning and terrestrial photogrammetry to quantify rock falls/avalanches in steep high-alpine rock walls (2007) Geophys. Res. Abstr, 9, p. 07170; Rosser, N.J., Terrestrial laser scanning for monitoring the process of hard rock coastal cliff erosion (2005) Q. J. Eng. Geol. Hydrogeol, 38, pp. 363-375","Rabatel, A.; Laboratoire Edytem, CNRS, Université de Savoie, F-73376 Le Bourget du Lac, France; email: antoine.rabatel@univ-savoie.fr",,,,,,,,00948276,,GPRLA,,"English","Geophys. Res. Lett.",Article,Scopus,2-s2.0-58049121924
